  "common_questions": [
    {
      "q": "What is Cortex Harness?",
      "a": "A forkable framework that turns the Mnemo Cortex memory layer into a memory-backed agent for a specific business. You fork it, set your business name and pick a vertical in one config file, run `python -m harness build`, and you get a runnable workspace: brain lanes, a memory-backend config carrying a business rule-set, an MCP config scoped to the tools you enabled, and launch scripts."
    },
    {
      "q": "How is it different from just using Mnemo Cortex directly?",
      "a": "Mnemo Cortex is the memory engine. Cortex Harness is the layer on top that makes the three things every business customizes first-class and config-driven: the agent's brain/identity (brain templates), how cautious it is (persona rule-sets), and which memory tools it sees (the tool loader). Without the harness you wire those by hand for each business; with it, you edit one file and build."
    },
    {
      "q": "What is a vertical?",
      "a": "A vertical is a business type, shipped as a folder under verticals/: a vertical.yaml (title, recommended persona + tool profile, any custom personas), a rules.md rule-set, and brain templates (identity, playbook). Five ship in the box: small-business, ecommerce, art-studio, writing, and day-trading. Everything in verticals/_base/ is inherited, so a new vertical only states what is different."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does the day-trading vertical place trades or give financial advice?",
      "a": "No. The day-trading vertical is a trading journal and research desk only — analysis and record-keeping. It never places orders, moves money, or tells the user to buy or sell, and it states plainly that nothing it says is financial advice. This is enforced in the persona's system prompt, the rule-set, and the brain lanes — and structurally: the tool catalog contains no broker or execution tool, so there is nothing to place a trade with. Its highest value is holding the trader to their OWN written rules."
    },
    {
      "q": "When I disable a tool, is the agent truly blocked from using it?",
      "a": "Today the enabled-tools set scopes the agent at the instruction level: the generated brain/tools.md lane tells the agent exactly which tools to use, and the set is recorded in the build's mcp.json as HARNESS_ENABLED_TOOLS for hosts that honor an allow-list. Hard host-level gating — the Mnemo Cortex bridge filtering tool registration down to the allow-list — is on the roadmap. Until then, treat the tool loader as scoping plus documentation, not a hard security boundary."
    },
    {
      "q": "How do I add my own vertical?",
      "a": "Copy a vertical folder under verticals/, edit vertical.yaml (title, recommended persona/profile), write rules.md (your business rules, supports {{placeholders}}), and add brain templates (00-identity.md, 20-playbook.md). Set business.vertical to your folder name and build. _base/ is inherited automatically, so you only state what differs."
    },
    {
      "q": "What does a build actually produce?",
      "a": "build/<slug>/ containing: brain/ (rendered identity/rules/tools/playbook lanes), agentb.yaml (the Mnemo Cortex backend config carrying your persona rule-set), mcp.json (MCP client config with your enabled tools + the bridge pointed at your brain dir), start.sh and start.ps1 (launch the memory backend), TOOLS.md (what the loader turned on and dropped), and manifest.json (a machine-readable record). Regenerate anytime; edits to generated files are overwritten."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is Mnemo Cortex bundled into this repo?",
      "a": "No — it is a separate clone you place alongside the harness as ./mnemo-cortex, and it is kept out of this repo by .gitignore (a dependency, not vendored). Clone it next to the harness, or point memory.mnemo_cortex_path at an existing checkout."
    }
  ],

