  "why": "Your AI forgets everything between sessions, and wiring up a memory system for a specific business — a bakery, an online store, a writing project — means repeating the same fiddly setup every time. Cortex Harness does that setup for you. You pick the kind of business you're running, fill in your name in one file, and it builds you an assistant that remembers across sessions, follows rules you can set (how careful it is, what it's allowed to guess at, what needs your sign-off), and only has the abilities you switch on. It runs on your own computer, your data stays local, and adding a new kind of business is just copying a folder.",

  "install_steps": [
    {"step": 1, "instruction": "Make sure you have Python 3.10 or newer."},
    {"step": 2, "instruction": "Download the harness: run 'git clone https://github.com/GuyMannDude/cortex-harness.git' and go into the new 'cortex-harness' folder."},
    {"step": 3, "instruction": "Get the memory layer it builds on: from inside that folder run 'git clone https://github.com/GuyMannDude/mnemo-cortex.git ./mnemo-cortex'."},
    {"step": 4, "instruction": "Install the one dependency the harness needs: 'pip install -r requirements.txt' (it's just PyYAML)."},
    {"step": 5, "instruction": "See what you can build with 'python -m harness list', then check your setup with 'python -m harness doctor'."},
    {"step": 6, "instruction": "Open harness.config.yaml and set your business name and pick a vertical (e.g. small-business). Preview with 'python -m harness plan', then compile with 'python -m harness build'."},
    {"step": 7, "instruction": "Run it: 'python -m harness run' builds and launches the memory backend. Point your AI app (Claude Desktop, Claude Code, etc.) at the generated build/<you>/mcp.json."}
  ],

  "works_with": [
    {"name": "Claude Code", "how": "Point it at the generated build/<you>/mcp.json, or add the Mnemo Cortex bridge entry that file describes."},
    {"name": "Claude Desktop", "how": "Copy the mcpServers block from the generated mcp.json into claude_desktop_config.json and restart."},
    {"name": "OpenClaw / Hermes Agent", "how": "Register the Mnemo Cortex MCP bridge from the generated mcp.json; the harness pre-fills BRAIN_DIR and the enabled-tools list."},
    {"name": "LM Studio / AnythingLLM / Open WebUI", "how": "Add the generated stdio MCP server entry in the app's settings."},
    {"name": "Mnemo Cortex", "how": "Required dependency — the harness compiles its backend config and launches it. 'python -m harness run' starts it for you."}
  ],

  "extensibility": "Adding a vertical is the whole point. Copy a folder under verticals/, edit vertical.yaml (title, recommended persona and tool profile, any custom personas), write your rules.md (plain markdown, supports {{placeholders}} like the business name), and add brain templates (00-identity.md for who the agent is, 20-playbook.md for how it works day to day). Everything in verticals/_base/ — shared identity, memory protocol, base rules — is inherited automatically, so you only write what is different. Set business.vertical to your folder name and build. The tool catalog (harness/tools_catalog.yaml) is editable too: add or regroup the memory-layer tools a build can expose, with per-tool prerequisites the loader validates. Everything is MIT-licensed and built to be forked.",

  "tips": [
    "Run `python -m harness plan` before building — it shows the persona and exactly which tools would be enabled vs dropped (and why), without writing anything.",
    "Blank fields in harness.config.yaml fall back to the vertical's recommended defaults — leave rules.persona empty to use the vertical's recommended rule-set.",
    "The generated brain/rules.md and brain/tools.md are rebuilt from live config on every build, so they can never drift from what was actually compiled. Don't hand-edit them — change the vertical or the config and rebuild.",
    "A tool whose prerequisite is missing is dropped with a reason, not silently exposed — e.g. mnemo_share needs memory.isolation: shared. Check the plan output to see what dropped.",
    "memory.isolation controls whether this agent's store is isolated, shared with other agents, or hybrid — it gates the cross-agent tools.",
    "The day-trading vertical is analysis-and-journal only by design — there is no execution tool anywhere in the catalog. It enforces YOUR written trading rules; it never tells you to buy or sell.",
    "Before production, add reasoning/embedding provider blocks to the generated agentb.yaml (see mnemo-cortex/agentb.yaml.example)."
